{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512837"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:02:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:02:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11968"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11968","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11968"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.82,0.04,0.02,0.11,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4560"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53384"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4560"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11968"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38839"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"197"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"2201"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6826"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6840"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53384","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53384"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old woman is currently being treated as an inpatient for chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) exacerbation. She has a medical history of COPD, atrial fibrillation, diabetes mellitus type 2, hypertension and obesity. Her medications include Seretide inhaler (fluticasone/salmeterol), salbutamol pMDI PRN, digoxin, metformin and perindopril. Due to initial poor oral intake, she had been commenced on electrolyte replacement both orally and intravenously. She is continued on supplements despite improving oral intake. Her potassium level is 6.1 mmol/L [3.5-5.0]. An ECG shows increased T wave amplitude.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Calcium gluconate","Resonium","Sodium bicarbonate","Insulin/dextrose infusion","Salbutamol nebuliser"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn scenarios where ECG findings of hyperkalaemia such as increased T wave amplitude, P wave flattening are present, cardiac membrane stabilisation is of utmost priority to prevent the development of dangerous arrhythmias. Calcium in the form of \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalcium gluconate\u003C/strong\u003E is given. Precaution should be undertaken and infusion time lengthened when administering calcium to a patient on digoxin as calcium can potentiate the effects of digoxin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsulin/dextrose infusion\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Esalbutamol nebuliser\u003C/strong\u003E are both quick ways of shifting potassium into cells. These treatment options are suitable for moderate to severe hyperkalaemia and are given concurrently with calcium chloride. However, protecting the heart remains the key priority.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EResonium\u003C/strong\u003E, sodium polystyrene sulfate, is given through the oral route and is appropriate for mild hyperkalaemia to enhance potassium elimination from the body. It is an ion exchange resin, which works in the gut to exchange sodium ions for potassium ions. The potassium is then passed and excreted in the faeces. As a result, it should not be used if the patient is constipated or has a post-op ileus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium bicarbonate\u003C/strong\u003E can be given as an IV infusion. However, it has limited efficacy and therefore, is used as an adjunct in the context of hyperkalaemia with metabolic acidosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cardiac membrane stabilisation is a priority in hyperkalaemia with ECG changes."],"references":["Buttner R, Burns E. Hyperkalaemia. In: LITFL - Life in the FastLane. 2022 [cited 2022 Aug 13]. Available at: https://litfl.com/hyperkalaemia-ecg-library/","Salyer SW. Chapter 8 - Medical Emergencies. Essential Emergency Medicine, W.B. Saunders. 2007;311-417."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38839"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11968"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38839","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38839"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-20T08:57:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-20T08:57:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4560"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53384"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"create